\cf2\b\fs32 **(28) Why is Google connectivity services allowed internet access by default?**\par
\cf0\b0\fs22\par
The Google connectivity services system application checks if the current network is really connected to the internet.\par
This is probably done by briefly connecting to some Google server.\par
\par
If this is not the case, there will be an '!' in the Wi-Fi or mobile icon in the system status bar.\par
\par
Recent Android versions seem not to switch connectivity from mobile to Wi-Fi when the Wi-Fi network is not really connected,\par
even though there is a connection to the Wi-Fi network (or the other way around). On Android 6.0 and later you might get a notification asking you if you want to keep this connection on or not.\par
To prevent a bad user experience there is a predefined rule to default allow the Google connectivity services.\par
\par
\par
