\cf2\b\fs32 **(30) Can I also run AFWall+ on the same device?**\cf0\b0\fs22\par
\par
Unless you are just testing NetSaver Pro, there is no current reason to use them both, since they cover the same function (firewall),\par
although with different base needs (AFWall+ needs a rooted device) and ways of doing their thing (AFWall+ uses iptables).\par
\par
Also you need to keep per applicaton access rules _always_ in sync,\par
else the application will not be able to access the network,\par
hence bringing another level of complexity when setting and assuring things work out.\par
\par
Some pointers on how to set up AFWall+:\par
* if not using filtering in NetSaver Pro, applications _need_ direct internet access (Wi-Fi and/or mobile) in AFWall+\par
* if using filtering, NetSaver Pro will _need_ internet access (Wi-Fi and/or mobile) in AFWall+\par
* if using filtering, when you un/reinstall NetSaver Pro, remember to RE-allow NetSaver Pro in AFWall+\par
* if using filtering, applications _need_ VPN internet access (check the box to show that option in AFWall+ settings)\par
\par
\cf2\b\fs28\par
**(31) Why can some applications be configured as a group only?**\par
\cf0\b0\fs22\par
For a lot of purposes, including network access, Android groups applications on UID and not on package/application name.\par
Especially system applications often have the same UID, despite having a different package and application name, these are set up like this by the ROM manufacturer at build time.\par
These applications can only be allowed/blocked access to the internet as a group.\par
\par
\cf2\b\fs32 **(32) Why is the battery/network usage of NetSaver Pro so high?**\cf0\b0\fs22\par
\par
This is because Android contributes battery and network usage which is normally contributed to other applications\par
to NetSaver Prod in IP filtering mode. The total battery usage is slightly higher when IP filtering mode is enabled.\par
IP filtering mode is always enabled on Android version before 5.0 and optionally enabled on later Android versions.\par
\par
\cf2\b\fs32 **(33) Can you add profiles?**\par
\cf0\b0\fs22\par
Profiles are inconvenient because they need to be operated manually.\par
Conditions like '*When screen is on*' are on the other hand convenient because they work automatic.\par
Therefore profiles will not be added, but you are welcome to propose new conditions,\par
however they need to be generally usable to be included.\par
\par
As a workaround you can use the export/import function to apply specific settings in specific circumstances.\par
\cf2\b\fs32\par
**(34) Can you add the condition 'when on foreground'?**\par
\cf0\b0\fs22\par
Recent Android versions do not allow an application to query if other applications are in the foreground or background anymore,\par
so this cannot be added. You can use the condition '*when screen is on*' instead.\par
\par
\cf2\b\fs32 **(35) Why does the VPN not start?**\par
\cf0\b0\fs22\par
NetSaver Pro "asks" Android to start the local VPN service,\par
but some Android versions contain a bug which prevents the VPN from starting (automatically).\par
Sometimes this is caused by updating NetSaver Pro.\par
Unfortunately this cannot be fixed from NetSaver Pro.\par
What you can try is to restart your device and/or revoke the VPN permissions from NetSaver Pro using the Android settings.\par
Sometimes it helps to uninstall and install NetSaver Pro again (be sure to export your settings first).\par
\par
\par
\cf2\b\fs32 **(36) Can you add PIN or password protection?**\cf0\fs24\par
\b0\fs22\par
Since turning off the VPN service using the Android settings cannot be prevented,\par
there is little use in adding PIN or password protection.\par
\par
\cf2\b\fs32 **(37) Why are the pro features so expensive?**\par
\cf0\b0\fs22\par
The right question is "*why are there so many taxes and fees*":\par
\par
* VAT: 25% (depending on your country)\par
* Google fee: 30%\par
* Income tax: 50%\par
\par
So, what is left for the developer is just a fraction of what you pay.\par
\par
Despite NetSaver Pro being *really* a lot of work, only some of the convenience and advanced features are paid,\par
which means that NetSaver Pro  is basically free to use.\par
\par
Also note that most free applications will appear not to be sustainable in the end, whereas NetSaver Pro is properly maintained and supported.\par
